Text.Value: That horn can be heard half the world away - let's issue a challenge, shall we?
No - you can't! I trusted you!

EditorData.NodeContext: Upset, the player has given up the entire tiefling grove for slaughter.

Text.Value: No, you don't get it. I'm with them.
What do you think? Ready for battle - and leave the drow to me.
A bold plan - but a risky one.
Simplest strategy there is: draw them in and burn them faster than they can burn us.
That's why our every ounce of anything that goes boom is buried out in front of that gate.
That's the stupidest damn plan I've ever heard.
Hold on - what's the plan again?
On to the city. After what you showed us, I damn well pity any who try and keep us out.
Who knows - with your help, might be we can even make a fight of it.
What happened?! We've spotted goblins massing in the woods.
Hah! Enough warriors to make this a fair fight. Failing that, we've got the means to make it unfair.

EditorData.NodeContext: Faint, joking - forced humour but knows no-one is buying it

Text.Value: For the glory of the Absolute. Why else?
To burn the grove, of course. For the glory of the Absolute.
Best news I've heard all day.

EditorData.NodeContext: Keen to start celebrating.

Text.Value: No two ways about it, now - a fight it'll have to be.

EditorData.NodeContext: Fatalistic, discarding any hope of escape but steeling himself for the fight

Text.Value: Well - are we ready? Tymora's spun her coin, and I would see which way it lands.
That horn can be heard half the world away - let's issue a challenge, eh?

EditorData.NodeContext: Acknowledging his plan is terrible but knows it's the only option.

Text.Value: I have a god to please, and Myrkul loves a slaughter.
I'd given you up for dead at the goblin camp - and our hopes along with you.
But if you're willing to spit in Lady Doom's eye along with us, I won't turn you down.
A trap? We're the ones backed into a corner here, I'd say.
All part of the plan. I'll give the signal and she'll march into our trap.
Gods damn it, I'm sorry. I know you wouldn't draw her on us.
Here - it's not much, but it's yours. Zevlor ordered a collection, before...

EditorData.NodeContext: Giving us a reward, and being reminded that his leader is either dead or disappeared. Trailing off to a painful memory (pulling himself back to the present in his next lines)

Text.Value: Won't pretend I expected to see you back again. Bloody glad, mind.

EditorData.NodeContext: Blunt, pleasantly surprised

Text.Value: Let the bastards know we're waiting for them.
We're ready to celebrate. Are you?
Gods, they're going to want a bloody speech, aren't they?
Give me a moment. I have more to do.
...A drow. Right - I'd say I'm surprised, but Beshaba's had her mark on us since Elturel.

EditorData.NodeContext: You've just told him he's facing insurmountable odds, and he's reacting with fear but resigned pragmatism. His outlook tends to be of the 'Murphy's Law' variety

Text.Value: How did you -
I have a god to please, and Bhaal loves murder.
Fact is, we can't beat 'em - not in a fair fight. So best make it as unfair as possible, eh?
My students are down in the cave. With wooden bloody swords, Torm spare me.

EditorData.NodeContext: Resigned - never thought he'd be training children to fight.

Text.Value: I'd sooner start this on our terms than theirs.
I have a god to please, and Myrkul loves a slaughter.
She tricked me. But I mean to make up for it.
We've just got word - the goblins have cleared out. And I hear it's you we have to thank.

EditorData.NodeContext: Delighted - impressed and proud of you.

Text.Value: Well to the hells with you - and your god and all. Guards! Weapons!

EditorData.NodeContext: Defiant, furious

Text.Value: As we'll ever be. Let's go.
We'll need every blade if we're to make a fight of this.
Come. It's time to paint the place red.
He's having words with Kagha. Reckon you don't want to miss that, but come find us after.
Burning drow sounds a pretty good option to me - but we'll have to get her here first.

EditorData.NodeContext: Firm. He's reached a decision, even if it is a dangeorus one.

Text.Value: Not so risky. Drow are cunning buggers, aye - but proud too, the way I hear it.
Gods, thought I was seeing a bloody ghost. How did you survive the goblin camp?
'Make up for it'? How the bloody hells -
Of course. Tell me what you need.
A... a drow? Why the hells would you bring her here?
Well to the hells with you, then. Guards - weapons!

EditorData.NodeContext: Defiant, furious

Text.Value: What? You think a bloodline makes us allies?
Simple - the goblins are a lot more useful to me.
I met the drow commanding them - and led her here.
I have a god to please, and Bhaal loves murder.
If we've got any chance at all, it'll be with you on our side.
Watching gods - while I was training children, you were out cutting down an entire goblin camp.
My people would be honoured to join your camp tonight, if you'll have us. We're ready to go when you are.
I'll let you know when I'm ready.
Aye, fair enough. Just don't take too long.
Oh aye, we've been busy. Fact is, we won't win in a fair fight - so best make it as unfair as we can.

EditorData.NodeContext: Wry

Text.Value: Wyll told me you gave us up to the goblins - bloody glad he had it wrong.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grimly relieved - he's found out you're on his side. Wyll = Will

Text.Value: You've cleared the way for us - as clear as it gets, anyway. Thank you.
Watching gods, but you're a prettier sight than any I expected to see today.

EditorData.NodeContext: He's relieved to see you, but warning of the impending attack - player might just have jumped out of the frying pan and into the fire.
EditorData.logicalname: Zevlor is DEAD + coming from entrance

Text.Value: You've turned on us? Hells, why?
But... aye, I trust you, Torm spare me. You've seen us right once before.
It's a trap - and she's waiting for my signal. Don't quibble with me now.
You don't owe us any apologies - but I'll take your help, if you're offering.
Trap a drow? Easier trap a spider in its own damned web!
That's it? Please tell me you've thought of another option.
Before he passed. But the time for mourning's done. I mean to celebrate.

EditorData.NodeContext: First sentence stating a painful truth about their leader having died, but firmly pulling himself back to be pragmatic and positive.

Text.Value: Though - you might want to speak to Halsin first. He turned up a short while ago.
She's expecting to find us broken - let's show her just what a mistake she's made.
You said it's a drow in charge, yeah? They ain't stupid, so I hear - but they are proud.
To think I was scared of a bloody drow. Should've known better - we had you.
Their drow commander found the grove - and she means to take it.
It's a full war-band, led by a drow.
Not after you've already saved us once before. We'll need your help again now.
I don't... Oh, gods.

EditorData.NodeContext: It takes him a moment to realise what he's being told - that the player has betrayed them and sided with the goblins.

Text.Value: You've reinforced the place - those barricades might even hold.
Traitor. The Blade now comes for you.
Just give the word.

EditorData.NodeContext: Friendly, waiting for you.

Text.Value: People are scared. Zevlor's doing what he can, but...

EditorData.NodeContext: Growing grim

Text.Value: Well. Seeing you on the walls might put the steel in their spines. Mine, too.
No doubt - but thick as I might be, I reckon this drow is likely twice as proud.

EditorData.NodeContext: Smiling, laughing, acknowledging his plan is terrible but knows it's the only option.

Text.Value: You helped us throw them back once before - fancy doing it again?

EditorData.NodeContext: Forced lightness, camraderie - he needs you to say yes

Text.Value: Sound the horn - let the bastards know we're waiting for them.
We won. We bloody won.
We'll have to lure them in first.
Sound the horn, then.
...A drow. Right - I'd say I'm surprised, but Beshaba's had her mark on us since Elturel.

EditorData.NodeContext: You've just told him he's facing insurmountable odds, and he's reacting with fear but resigned pragmatism. His outlook tends to be of the 'Murphy's Law' variety

Text.Value: What's the plan?
More importantly - what happened? We've spotted them massing in the woods.
Once we're ready, we'll draw 'em in to that spot. Then it's down to fire-arrows and prayer.
I'm ready to go to camp now.
...A drow. Right - I'd say I'm surprised, but Beshaba's had her mark on us since Elturel.

EditorData.NodeContext: You've just told him he's facing insurmountable odds, and he's reacting with fear but resigned pragmatism. His outlook tends to be of the 'Murphy's Law' variety

Synopsis:
Asharak has been tasked with getting civilians prepared for war. He hopes having the player on their side might make the difference.
If the tiefling leader is dead, Asharak reluctantly steps into his shoes.
